;Digital Inclusion means practicing respect
Ri nimoj kemtz'ib' nuq'ajuj chi niya' ruq'ij ri kamelanïk


;We should all have the ability to participate fully on the Internet, without threat to our reputations, our confidence, or our safety.
Konojel k'o chi yojtikïr yojto'on rik'in ri K'amaya'l, akuchi' majun k'ayewal nipe chi qij, ri qakuqub'al k'u'x o chuqa' ri qajikomal.


;We’ve all seen our share of nasty comments sections. At times, the Web can feel like a very unfriendly place – particularly for women, minorities, and members of marginalized communities. By discouraging people from getting online, cyberbullying and cyber violence threaten not just individuals, but the Internet itself.
Qonojel qatz'eton ri peraj richin itzel taq rutzijol. K'o re, ri Ajk'amaya'l nina' chi jun itzel k'ojlib'äl – achi'el chi kiwäch ri ixoqi', ri e jub'a' ok chuqa' ri e ruwinaq q'eleb'en taq tinamït. Nuqasaj kik'u'x ri winaqi' richin yek'oje' pa k'amaya'l, achi'el ri yoq'k'am chuqa' ri itzelanel k'amil, ri man xa xe ta yerutz'ila' winaqi' xa chuqa' nutz'ila' ri k'amaya'l


;73% of Internet users have seen someone harassed online and 40% have personally experienced it.
73% chi ke ri ruwinaq K'amaya'l rutz'eton chi k'o jun, ri xtz'iläx pa k'amab'ey chuqa' ri 40% chuqa' kik'ulwachin chik.


;Source: <a href="%(pew)s">Pew Research</a>, 2014
Xe'el: <a href="%(pew)s">Ruk'ojlib'al kanonïk</a>, 2014


